<F P=100> PRC MEDIA ON TAIWAN AFFAIRS </F>
<H3> <TI>   State Council Spokesman Welcomes Taiwan Officials' Visits </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  OW3101203694 Beijing XINHUA Domestic Service in Chinese 0834 
GMT 29 Jan 94 </F>

<F P=103> OW3101203694 </F>
<F P=104>  Beijing XINHUA Domestic Service </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Chinese </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Beijing, 29 Jan (XINHUA) -- A spokesman of the 
Taiwan Affairs Office of the State Council today made a 
statement on Taiwan's allowing officials to take part in 
exchange activities on the mainland in a private capacity. He 
pointed out: In recent years, nongovernment exchanges between 
the two sides of the strait have become increasingly active. 
Exchange activities of various kinds and forms have taken place 
constantly on both sides of the strait. Those exchanges and 
contacts have enhanced understanding and affection [gan qing 
1949 1906] between people of the two sides. They are conducive 
to developing relations between the two sides, and the good 
results will benefit both sides. 
  He said: In past exchange activities, a small number of 
officials among the Taiwan authorities had come to the mainland 
to take part in exchange activities in a private capacity. We 
have always taken a attitude welcoming such activities. 
According to a recent report by Taiwan newspapers, the Taiwan 
authorities will relax restrictions and allow Taiwan officials 
to go to the mainland for cultural and educational exchange 
activities in the name of academic or mass organizations. We 
express our welcoming of this decision by the Taiwan 
authorities. Meanwhile, we hope that officials of the Taiwan 
side, when they come to the mainland for exchange or other 
nongovernment activities in a private capacity, will first 
contact the Taiwan's Straits Exchange Foundation and the 
mainland's Association for Relations Across the Taiwan Straits 
so as to let concerned departments on the mainland provide 
necessary asssitance. This will enable such exchange activities 
to be conducted in a smooth and proper manner and to achieve 
good results. 
  The spokesman of the Taiwan Affairs Office said: We hope the 
Taiwan authorities will adopt a similar attitude to promote 
exchanges between the two sides of the strait, further relax 
restrictions, and allow mainland officials to go to Taiwan to 
take part in exchange activities in a personal or private 
capacity. 

</TEXT>

