<H3> <TI>   Delegation To Meet Congressional Leaders in Washington </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  OW0102082894 Taipei CNA in English 0710 GMT 1 Feb 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW0102082894 </F>
<F P=104>  Taipei CNA </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [By Bill Wang] </F>
  [Text] Washington, Jan. 31 (CNA) -- A Republic of China 
[ROC] delegation, led by Kuomintang Secretary-General Hsu 
Shui-teh, arrived here Monday [31 January] to attend Thursday's 
1994 national prayer breakfast. 
  The delegation was greeted at Dulles International Airport 
by 
Ding Mou-shih, Taipei's representative in Washington, and 
representatives of the Chinese community here. 
  Hsu dismissed reports that he would be a candidate in the 
forthcoming Taiwan provincial governor election, saying that in 
his capacity as party secretary-general, he must try to find 
another more qualified candidate for the job. 
  On Tuesday, the delegation will meet with Haley Barbour, 
chairman of the Republican National Committee, and congressional 
leaders, including Senate majority leader George Mitchell 
(D-Maine), Minority Leader Bob Dole (R-Kan.), Sen. Charles Robb 
(D-Va.), chairman of the senate committee on Asia and Pacific 
affairs, and Rep. Gary Ackerman (D-N.Y.) chairman of the house 
subcommitte on Asia and Pacific affairs. 
  On Wednesday, they will meet with Natale Bellocchi, chairman 
of the American Institute in Taiwan. 
  They will attend the national prayer breakfast Thursday and 
later in the day meet with Jim Brady, vice chairman of the 
Democratic National Committee (DNC), and Debra Delee, DNC vice 
chairman and executive director. 
  During their three-day stay here, they will also meet with 
members of the Chinese community in the Washington area. 

</TEXT>

