<F P=100> Taiwan </F>
<H3> <TI>   SEF Vice Chairman Leaves for Beijing Talks </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  OW3101091994 Taipei CNA in English 0728 GMT 31 Jan 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW3101091994 </F>
<F P=104>  Taipei CNA </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [By Debbie Kuo] </F>
  [Text] Taipei, Jan. 31 (CNA) -- Chiao Jen-ho, vice 
chairman and secretary-general of Straits Exchange Foundation 
(SEF), left for Beijing Monday [31 January] morning to meet his 
mainland Chinese counterpart Tang Shubei for a new round of 
cross-Taiwan strait talks. 
  Although this round of talks might also end without reaching 
agreement Chiao said at the airport, "The increase in mutual 
trust is a positive development." 
  Chiao's meeting with Tang, vice chairman and 
secretary-general of the Beijing-based Association for Relations 
Across the Taiwan Strait (ARATS), was arranged based on an 
accord reached during the talks between SEF Chairman Ku Chen-fu 
and ARATS Chairman Wang Daohan last April in Singapore. The 
accord calls for quarterly meetings between SEF and ARATS 
officials of the deputy secretary-general or department director 
level. 
  The Chiao-Tang talks will take place Tuesday and Wednesday 
afternoons and Friday morning at the Diaoyutai State Guest House. 
  They will focus on reviewing the results of the three cross- 
strait technical talks held last year in the hope that more 
progress can be made during future discussions. 
  The two heads of the intermediary organizations will also 
look into the operations of both SEF and ARATS as well as review 
the implementation of the agreements signed during the 
"Ku-Wang" talks. 
  Issues related to a second "Ku-Wang" meeting will also be 
considered during the talks, according to one of Chiao's aides. 
  Chiao was traveling in the company of SEF Deputy 
Secretaries-General Shih Chi-ping and Hsu Huei-yu. 
  SEF Chief Secretary Wu Shu, who arrived in Beijing three 
days 
ago, held a meeting Saturday with ARATS Deputy Secretary-General 
Zhao Zhengyu, to prepare for the forthcoming talks. 

</TEXT>

