<F P=100> Taiwan </F>
<H3> <TI>   Direct Shipping Left Off Agenda of Mainland Work Meeting </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  OW2801050894 Taipei TZU LI WAN PAO in Chinese 12 Jan 94 p 2 </F>
<F P=103> OW2801050894 </F>
<F P=104>  Taipei TZU LI WAN PAO </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Chinese </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [By reporter Chang Yu-ying] </F>
  [Text] Chen Ming-chang, director of Economic Affairs under 
the Mainland Affairs Council [MAC], today [12 January] said that 
the issue of "direct shipping between designated points" across 
the strait will definitely not be put on the agenda of a meeting 
to review mainland work that has been slated for 6-7 June this 
year. However, it has been learned that the MAC has arranged for 
its Vice Chairman Kao Koong-lian to personally explain to the 
people our policy and stand vis-a-vis why it is inappropriate 
for cross-strait "direct shipping between designated points" at 
the present stage. 
  It has been learned that the MAC still holds that before the 
removal of substantive barriers in politics, law, and security 
confronting the issue of direct navigation between the two sides 
of the strait, various forms of shipping links such as "direct 
shipping between designated points" and "unilateral opening to 
shipping" may just slightly improve on the subject of opening up 
navigation in terms of volume or mode, but their practicality is 
not great. Nevertheless, the MAC still has not ruled out the 
possibility of carrying out such a link as "direct shipping 
between designated points" or "unilateral opening to shipping" 
in the initial stage as a transitional measure after direct 
navigation has been opened up. 

</TEXT>

