<F P=100> Taiwan </F>
<H3> <TI>   Ministry Approves Indirect Investment in Mainland Leasing </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  OW3101043594 Taipei China Broadcasting Corporation News 
Network in Mandarin 2300 GMT 20 Jan 94 </F>

<F P=103> OW3101043594 </F>
<F P=104>  Taipei China Broadcasting Corporation News 
Network </F>



<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Mandarin </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [From the "Hookup" program] </F>
  [Text] The prohibition on investment in the mainland by 
building, engineering consulting, and leasing traders has been 
lifted conditionally. The Ministry of Economic Affairs 
yesterday held the first meeting of the special task force on 
examining applications for investment in the mainland. The 
meeting approved for the first time indirect investment in the 
mainland by building, engineering consulting, and leasing 
traders. In addition, the meeting also, in principle, gave a 
green signal to indirect investment in the mainland by passenger 
transportation traders. Due to incomplete application data 
submitted by the traders for examination at the meeting, the 
ministry will hold its official approval to the passenger 
transportation trade until the next meeting of the special task 
force. 
  In accordance with the principles for examining investment 
and technology cooperation projects in the mainland, promulgated 
on 31 December last year, the ministry convened the first 
meeting of the supra-ministerial special task force yesterday. 
At the meeting, representatives from various ministries 
examined 18 projects on investment in the mainland. As the 
Construction and Planning Administration under the Interior 
Ministry insisted that examination for applications from 
building and construction traders must be separated, Li 
Shu-chiu, executive vice minister of economic affairs who 
chaired the meeting, said: Building traders may invest in the 
mainland conditionally; however, the prohibition shall continue 
to be enforced on construction traders planning to invest mainly 
in development and marketing projects in the mainland. 

</TEXT>

