<F P=100> Northeast Asia </F>
<H3> <TI>   Japanese Official Reaffirms Nation's Nonnuclear Status </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  OW3101163794 Beijing XINHUA in English 1616 GMT 31 Jan 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW3101163794 </F>
<F P=104>  Beijing XINHUA </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Tokyo, January 31 (XINHUA) -- Japanese Vice Foreign 
Minister Kunihiko Saito said today that Japan intends to adhere 
to its non-nuclear position. 
  He denied an allegation by a British newspaper that Japan 
may 
change its declared stance and develop a nuclear capability 
because of the rumored nuclear program of the Democratic 
People's Republic of Korea (DPRK). 
  Speaking at a press conference in Tokyo, the vice minister 
noted that Japan would maintain its 3-point non-nuclear 
principle of neither possessing nor producing nuclear weapons, 
and not allowing them on Japanese soil. He said that to do 
otherwise would only contribute to the instability of the 
international environment around Japan. 
  The British "SUNDAY TIMES" reported that Japan had acquired 
all the parts needed to make a nuclear weapon, and may have 
built a bomb which requires only plutonium to be completed. 

</TEXT>

