<F P=100> NATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<F P=101> Political &amp; Social </F>
<H3> <TI>   Minister Urges Improving Nationalities' Relations </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  HK0102062094 Beijing CHINA DAILY in English 1 Feb 94 p 1 </F>
<F P=103> HK0102062094 </F>
<F P=104>  Beijing CHINA DAILY </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [By staff reporter He Jun: "Call To Develop Minority </F>
Districts"] 
  [Text] The ethnic minority policy will be guided by the 
principles of unity, progress, stability and development, the 
State Nationalities Affairs Commission conference was told 
yesterday. 
  If these principles are followed ethnic relations will 
improve and China's national unity and social stability will be 
protected, Commission Vice-Chairman Chen Hong said. 
  Inter-ethnic relations improved markedly last year, as 
economic developments began to spread from the coastal areas to 
the interior and border regions, Chen said. 
  But increasing contact between the different nationality 
cultures had led to unavoidable arguments and conflict, 
Commission Minister Ismail Amat told the conference. 
  Amat urged central and local nationalities affairs 
departments to strengthen their conflict resolution work so as 
to safeguard social stability. 
  And he encouraged his colleagues to continue the fight 
against hostile forces from inside and outside China that 
attempted to split the country by playing the ethnic issue card. 
  Another national conference will be held in September this 
year to honour individuals and collectives that have made 
outstanding contributions to the unity and progress of Chinese 
nationalities, Chen said. 
  And he encouraged local government to arrange forums to push 
forward the nationalities work. And they should select nominees 
for the national honours. 
  Amat stressed the need to further strengthen the legislation 
on nationalities affairs and promote the reform and opening up 
in the ethnic regions. 

</TEXT>

