<F P=100> REGIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<F P=101> East Region </F>
<H3> <TI>   Shandong Leads in Attracting Foreign Funds </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  OW2901021294 Beijing XINHUA in English 0130 GMT 29 Jan 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW2901021294 </F>
<F P=104>  Beijing XINHUA </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Jinan, January 29 (XINHUA) -- East China's Shandong 
Province reported a remarkable increase in invested foreign 
funds last year, thanks to its improved infrastructure. 
  An official from the provincial foreign economic and trade 
commission said the province approved some 7,229 foreign-funded 
firms last year, involving a total contractual foreign 
investment of about 7 billion U.S. dollars, exceeding the total 
amount for the previous 14 years. 
  To date, business people from some 61 countries and regions 
in the world have established about 13,073 joint ventures in 
Shandong, with a total contractual foreign investment of some 
12.45 billion U.S. dollars, the official said. 
  He added that about 72 percent of the foreign-funded firms 
fall into the area of manufacturing and 28 percent are in such 
fields as agriculture, aquatic production, the service trade, 
energy, transportation and high technology. 
  The province has capitalized on its abundant natural 
resources and superior geographic situation and made painstaking 
efforts to improve its infrastructure over the past decade. 
  Shandong now has three international airports, more than 
50,000 km in highways and seven seaports open to the outside 
world with a total handling capacity of more than 90 million 
tons annually. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS3-25914 </DOCNO>
<HT>    "drchi021_o_94005" </HT>


