<F P=100> REGIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<F P=101> East Region </F>
<H3> <TI>   Shandong Peninsula Boosts Foreign Trade </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  OW0102060694 Beijing XINHUA in English 0531 GMT 1 Feb 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW0102060694 </F>
<F P=104>  Beijing XINHUA </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Qingdao, February 1 (XINHUA) -- The special 
economic zones in east China's Shandong peninsula have boosted 
their foreign trade markedly. 
  According to statistics, these zones exported 2.47 billion 
U.S. dollars-worth of goods last year, an increase of 78.7 
percent over the previous year. 
  The zones are located in the eight cities of Qingdao, 
Yantai, 
Weihai, Weifang, Zibo, Rizhao, Jinan and Dongying. 
  A local official attributed the good result to a positive 
expansion of foreign economic cooperation. 
  In addition to increases in imports and exports, a survey 
shows that these open cities, empowered to export their products 
by themselves, have absorbed foreign funds, offered labor 
service, opened enterprises overseas and conducted international 
tourist service. 
  Aiming for the international market, the peninsula has 
combined agriculture with industry and trade to form an 
all-embracing export-oriented setup. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

