<H3> <TI>   Shanghai Opens Housing Development to Foreigners </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  OW3101161194 Beijing XINHUA in English 1518 GMT 31 Jan 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW3101161194 </F>
<F P=104>  Beijing XINHUA </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Shanghai, January 31 (XINHUA) -- The Municipal 
Government of Shanghai, the largest industrial and commercial 
center in China, has approved a decision to allow foreign 
investors to engage in the development and management of 
commercial housing for domestic sales. 
  The decision applies to areas where dangerous, ramshackle 
houses and crowded old-style alleys account for more than 50 
percent of residential space. 
  Investors will enjoy preferential prices for the lease of 
land use rights and the limit for the lease of land use rights 
will be 70 years, according to the decision. 
  Under the decision, an investor may acquire land use rights 
after turning over to the government a sum of money. Investors 
will have to shoulder relocation fees and other expenses. 
  The foreign-funded commercial housing will be targeted at 
Chinese individuals, enterprises or institutions, the decision 
noted. 
  Investors will have to re-sign the contracts for the lease 
of 
land use rights if they want to sell the houses abroad, the 
decision pointed out. 

</TEXT>

