<F P=100> REGIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<F P=101> East Region </F>
<H3> <TI>   Zhejiang Forestry Sector Attracts Foreign Funds </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  OW0102094494 Beijing XINHUA in English 0914 GMT 1 Feb 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW0102094494 </F>
<F P=104>  Beijing XINHUA </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Hangzhou, February 1 (XINHUA) -- The forestry sector 
in east China's Zhejiang Province has attracted growing 
investment from abroad. 
  By the end of last year, foreign funds used by the forestry 
sector in Zhejiang amounted to about 60 million U.S. dollars and 
there are now 45 foreign-funded enterprises in this sphere in 
the province. 
  Foreign investors turned their attention to the raising of 
fruit trees, bamboo processing and tourist projects in forest 
areas. 
  The largest foreign-funded project in Zhejiang's forestry 
sector is an afforestation project funded by the World Bank, 
whose loans to the project amounted to about 2.8 million U.S. 
dollars. 
  The first three-year phase of the project has been carried 
out and Zhejiang has planted trees on an area of 46,200 hectares. 
  The second phase of the project will start in 1995. 
  The foreign funds have promoted the export of forest 
products 
in Zhejiang. Last year, the export value of forest products in 
Zhejiang was 250 million U.S. dollars. 

</TEXT>

