<F P=100> Northwest Region </F>
<H3> <TI>   `Hope Project' Enables Qinghai Dropouts To Return to School </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  OW2901064494 Beijing XINHUA in English 0613 GMT 29 Jan 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW2901064494 </F>
<F P=104>  Beijing XINHUA </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Xining, January 29 (XINHUA) -- With aid from the 
"Hope Project", some 12,350 children who dropped out of school 
in northwest China's Qinghai Province have returned to the 
classroom over the past three years. 
  The project was sponsored in 1989 by the Chinese Communist 
Youth League, in a bid to help children nationwide who have 
dropped out of school for various reasons to resume their 
studies. 
  In the past three years, the province's Hope Project 
Foundation has received some one million yuan in donations from 
about 260,000 home and overseas donors. 
  With these funds, the province has also established seven 
new 
"Hope primary schools" in its poverty-stricken areas. 
  Meanwhile, schools in such areas have received more than 
300,000 yuan worth of teaching aids as well as articles for 
daily use. 
  Located in the remote northeastern part of the Qinghai-Tibet 
plateau, the province is one of the most underdeveloped 
provinces in China. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

