<F P=100> Economic &amp; Agricultural </F>
<H3> <TI>   Wu Yi Sees `Gratifying Progress' </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  OW2901025594 Beijing XINHUA Domestic Service in Chinese 0745 
GMT 28 Jan 94 </F>

<F P=103> OW2901025594 </F>
<F P=104>  Beijing XINHUA Domestic Service </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Chinese </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [By RENMIN RIBAO reporter Gong Wen (7895 7186) and XINHUA </F>
reporter Jiang Jun (1203 6511)] 
  [Text] Beijing, 28 Jan (XINHUA) -- Speaking at a State 
Council Information Office news conference today, Wu Yi, 
minister of foreign trade and economic cooperation, said: China 
achieved gratifying progress in its trade and economic relations 
with foreign countries in 1993, with a total volume of exports 
and imports reaching $195.72 billion, up 18.2 percent from the 
preceding year. Of this, exports amounted to $91.77 billion and 
imports, $103.95 billion, up 8 percent and 29 percent 
respectively over 1992. 
  One of the outstanding characteristics of China's foreign 
trade in 1993 was the slow growth of exports and rapid increase 
of imports. Last year, China imported large amounts of raw and 
semifinished materials, energy, and equipment because of 
high-speed growth of the domestic economy, large scale 
investment, and robust demand. As a result, the increase of 
imports was 21 percentage points higher than that of exports, 
leaving a deficit of $12.18 billion. According to statistics, 
last year, imported commodities worth over $1 billion included 
mainly aircraft, automobiles, rolled steel, crude oil, finished 
oil, chemical fertilizers, industrial chemicals, and complete 
sets of equipment. Wu Yi pointed out: These imported 
commodities once again show that China is a large open market 
with great potential. She added that China will strive to 
strike a rough balance between exports and imports this year by 
increasing exports rather than reducing imports. 
  Foreign investment in China in 1993 was double that in 1992, 
and was almost equal to the total amount for the previous 14 
years. Last year, China approved 83,265 foreign-funded projects, 
with a total contractual value of $110.852 billion; and the 
actual amount of foreign investment used in the period was 
$25.759 billion. These figures were 70 percent, 90 percent, and 
134 percent, respectively, more than in 1992. The investment 
scale continually expanded, with an average contracted 
investment per foreign-funded project reaching $1.33 million, a 
12.9-percent increase over the $117.8 million of the previous 
year. The proportion of technology intensive projects and 
multinational corporations increased, and the area of investment 
was rapidly expanding to the hinterland. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

