<F P=100> Economic &amp; Agricultural </F>
<H3> <TI>   Banks To Start Foreign Exchange Operations </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  HK0102100294 Hong Kong TA KUNG PAO in Chinese 28 Jan 94 p 2 </F>
<F P=103> HK0102100294 </F>
<F P=104>  Hong Kong TA KUNG PAO </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Chinese </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> ["Special report" by staff reporter Ma Ling (7456 3781): </F>
"PRC Banks, Including Foreign-Funded Banks, To Start Foreign 
Exchange Transaction Operations as of 1 April"] 
  [Text] Beijing, 27 Jan (TA KUNG PAO)--Effective 1 April, 
the state is to allow some designated banks, including some 
foreign- funded banks, to carry out foreign exchange transaction 
operations, changing the present situation of the banks 
confining their operations to settlement of exchange. At that 
time, the State Foreign Exchange Administration will publish 
average foreign exchange prices based on the banks' transaction 
prices; that is, a floating exchange rate system with controls 
worthy of the name will begin, an authoritative figure disclosed. 
  According to this figure, at present, the Shanghai Foreign 
Exchange Transaction Center is making basic preparations for 
work in this area; and related state departments will make the 
final examination and decision and give approval. The 
designated banks would be members [as published] and have the 
right to conduct foreign exchange transaction operations. Some 
foreign-funded banks might also become members and carry out 
such operations should their applications be approved. In 
addition, they might entrust members to carry out operations in 
this area. 
  Since 1 January this year, the dual-track foreign exchange 
prices have been merged; generally speaking, however, no 
floating rates have been seen in the mainland foreign exchange 
market as of today. The explanation by this authoritative figure 
on this point was: The merger is still at the initial stage, 
and in a transition period at that; hence the plan has not been 
implemented to the full. The State Foreign Exchange 
Administration continues to use the right to fix the average 
prices based on the foreign exchange quotations provided by the 
18 foreign exchange regulation centers across China, that is, 
the previous foreign exchange transaction order is being 
maintained. After 1 April, the designated banks will start 
foreign exchange transaction operations, and then a floating 
exchange rate system with controls worthy of the name will have 
been founded; at that time, some minute fluctuations in foreign 
exchange quotations might surface. The authoritative figure 
especially emphasized that no major fluctuations would arise. 
  The authoritative figure said that with banks starting to 
conduct foreign exchange transaction operations, the existing 
foreign exchange regulation centers across China would face two 
sorts of conversion: First, the dozen or so major local foreign 
exchange centers would become branches of the national foreign 
exchange transaction center; and second, some of the foreign 
exchange regulation centers would be converted to economic 
companies, that is economic companies in the main providing 
foreign exchange information. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS3-25960 </DOCNO>
<HT>    "drchi021_n_94009" </HT>


<HEADER>
<AU>   FBIS-CHI-94-021 </AU>
Document Type:Daily Report 
<DATE1>  1 Feb 1994 </DATE1>

</HEADER>

<F P=100> Economic &amp; Agricultural </F>
<H3> <TI>   Foreign Exchange Swap Centers To Close by April </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  HK3101010494 Hong Kong SOUTH CHINA SUNDAY MORNING POST 
(SUNDAY MONEY) in English 30 Jan 94 p 1 </F>

<F P=103> HK3101010494 </F>
<F P=104>  Hong Kong SOUTH CHINA SUNDAY MORNING POST 
(SUNDAY MONEY) </F>



<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [By Kennis Chu] </F>
  [Text] Beijing plans to close all swap centres in the 
country by April 1. The move follows the announcement on 
December 29 that China was to scrap the dual exchange rate and 
float the yuan from January 1 this year. However, technical 
problems have prevented the new system from operating 
immediately. The first quarter of this year will be a 
transitional period when foreign exchange retention quotas will 
be gradually phased out and an embryonic interbank foreign 
exchange market will come into existence. 
  According to Tsang Shu-ki, senior lecture at Hong Kong 
Baptist College, Beijing aims to connect all swap centres with 
the new system in three months. By April 1, the National 
Foreign Exchange Centre, located in Shanghai, will supplant 
existing swap centres in China and will become a national 
interbank market for appointed banks to trade and settle foreign 
currencies. All enterprises will then have to exchange currency 
with appointed banks. He said: "It needs a transitionary period 
to transform swap-based currency trading into a bank-based one. 
  "By that time, Shanghai will become an interbank centre and 
those banks appointed can buy and sell currencies in the 
interbank market," added Mr Tsang, who has consulted a number of 
Chinese officials from various authorities in Beijing. Alex 
Tang, research director of Yamaichi International, said: "They 
should have enough time to connect all swap centres." 
  Previously, there were three exchange rates in China -- the 
swap rate (8.7 yuan to one U.S. dollar), the official rate (5.7 
yuan to one U.S. dollar) and the black market rate. Companies 
with approvals traded currencies at the 100 swap centres while 
foreigners and individuals with approvals exchanged the yuan at 
appointed mainland banks at an official rate. Under the new 
exchange system, all swap centres will be removed and approved 
enterprises will buy and sell hard currencies at appointed banks. 
  Shanghai's National Foreign Exchange Centre connects 
Beijing, 
Tianjin, Hangzhou, Shenzhen, Xiamen and Chengdu. "At present, 
the satellite network can provide information only. You can't 
make any transaction through the network," said a Shanghai 
source. 
  The national centre is supposed to play an interbank role. 
Beijing has yet to announce the list of members that will be 
allowed to trade at the centre. Mr Tsang estimated that only 
the four specialised banks--the Industrial and Commercial Bank 
of China, the Agricultural Bank of China, the Bank of China and 
the People's Construction Bank of China--and the China 
Investment Bank would be allowed to enter the centre. "The 
centre can not handle too many banks," he added. 
  The new exchange rate will be based on the daily average 
exchange rate traded at the centre one day before. Although the 
new system has already been introduced, details are scant. Like 
the old exchange trading method, the new system offers limited 
access, catering only to companies that need foreign currency 
for their operations. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

