<F P=100> United States &amp; Canada </F>
<H3> <TI>   XINHUA Notes Clauses on SRV, Korea, B-H in Senate Bill </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  OW0202223094 Beijing XINHUA in English 2155 GMT 2 Feb 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW0202223094 </F>
<F P=104>  Beijing XINHUA </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Washington, February 2 (XINHUA) -- The U.S. Senate 
today approved an authorization bill of 12.4 billion dollars for 
fiscal years 1994 and 1995 for the State Department, the U.S. 
Information Agency and the Peace Corps. 
  Attached to the bill, which was passed 92-8, were amendments 
calling for the unilateral lifting of arms embargo against 
Bosnia- Herzegovina and recommending the redeployment of 
tactical nuclear weapons in South Korea if no major progress was 
made in talks with the Democratic People's Republic of Korea on 
nuclear inspections. 
  Another amendment, passed last week, urges the Bill Clinton 
administration to end a 19-year-old trade embargo on Vietnam. 
  The amendments are not legally binding. 
  Clinton said today he might make a decision on the embargo 
in 
a few days. 
  According to the Senate bill, which still has to be 
reconciled with the House of Representatives, 900 million 
dollars will be provided for peacekeeping missions over the 
two-year period aside from an 175 million dollars requested for 
an international peacekeeping contingency fund. 
  The Senate bill also called for: 
  -- The quick inclusion of East European countries in the 
North Atlantic Treaty Organization as full members while 
praising the "Partnership for Peace" Program. 
  -- Cuts of 10 percent and 20 percent respectively for 1994 
and 1995 for U.S. contributions to the United Nations. 
  -- Blocking arms sales to countries that enforce the Arab 
League boycott on U.S. companies that do business with Israel. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

