<F P=100> United States &amp; Canada </F>
<H3> <TI>   White House Announces Offer for Somali Police Forces </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  OW0302044394 Beijing XINHUA in English 0428 GMT 3 Feb 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW0302044394 </F>
<F P=104>  Beijing XINHUA </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Washington, February 2 (XINHUA) -- U.S. President 
Bill Clinton has authorized 12 million dollars in U.S. aid to 
help re-establish police forces in Somalia, the White House 
announced here today. 
  Clinton said the money would come from U.S. funds previously 
appropriated for peacekeeping operations this fiscal year. 
  The President made the authorization in a memorandum to 
Secretary of State Warren Christopher that was released today by 
the White House. 
  The Clinton administration has announced withdrawal of all 
U.S. troops from Somalia by March 31. 
  Fears are increasing that Somali factions could be fighting 
again after U.S. forces and other nations' peacekeeping forces 
pull out. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS3-26073 </DOCNO>
