<F P=100> Central Eurasia </F>
<H3> <TI>   Kozyrev Says Moscow Opposes Air Raids in Bosnia </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  OW0202014694 Beijing XINHUA in English 0056 GMT 2 Feb 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW0202014694 </F>
<F P=104>  Beijing XINHUA </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Moscow, February 1 (XINHUA) -- Russian Foreign 
Minister Andrey Kozyrev said today that Moscow hopes the 
possible air raids in Bosnia-Herzegovina will not happen, 
stressing the need to hold additional talks over the issue. 
  At a meeting with visiting mediators Lord Owen and Thorvald 
Stoltenberg, co-chairmen of the international peace conference 
on the former Yugoslavia, Kozyrev described the planned air 
raids as "an extreme step." 
  Although in principle air raid is not excluded within the 
framework of UN Security Council resolutions, Kozyrev said, 
Moscow still keeps its initiative in the Security Council to 
make additional efforts to push for the peace process in the 
region. 
  Owen and Stoltenberg arrived here earlier today for 
discussion on measures to prevent violence in the Balkan region 
from further escalating, keep the Geneva negotiations process 
going and finally achieve a settlement. 
  The two peace mediators departed for Geneva this afternoon 
after their brief working visit here. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

