<F P=100> Central Eurasia </F>
<H3> <TI>   INTERFAX Cited on Russian-Georgian Treaty Issue </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  OW0302022494 Beijing XINHUA in English 0130 GMT 3 Feb 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW0302022494 </F>
<F P=104>  Beijing XINHUA </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Moscow, February 2 (XINHUA) -- Ivan Rybkin, 
chairman of the Russian parliament's state Duma (the lower 
house), said today that the lawmakers might reject the planned 
Russian-Georgian treaty of friendship and cooperation, the 
INTERFAX NEWS AGENCY reported. 
  In a message to President Boris Yeltsin, Rybkin said the 
treaty, scheduled to be signed on Thursday [3 February] at the 
summit between Yeltsin and Georgian leader Eduard Shevardnadze 
in Tbilisi, capital of Georgia, would destabilize the situation 
in the Caucasian region. 
  Under the treaty, Russia would help Georgia form its armed 
forces and supply it with military technology, the report said. 
  The Georgian parliament's deputy speaker Vakhtang 
Rcheulishvili said his nation expected "much from Yeltsin's 
visit," adding that the visit would mark the beginning of a new 
stage in relations between the two countries. 
  However, Sokrat Dzhindzholia, leader of the secessionist 
Abkhazia region of Georgia, Tuesday expressed his opposition to 
the Russian- Georgian treaty. 
  He stressed that such an agreement should be signed only 
after the conflict between Georgia and Abkhazia is completely 
settled and the latter's political status determined. 
  Abkhazia, an autonomous republic of Georgia, declared its 
independence from the central government in July 1992. Since 
then, the two sides have been involved in a bloody conflict. 
  Meanwhile, leaders of South Ossetia, another autonomous 
region of Georgia, accused Russia today of "inconsistency" in 
its approach to signing the treaty with Georgia. 
  South Ossetia has had a long-time military conflict with 
Georgia since it declared independence from Tbilisi in November 
1991. 
  South Ossetian leaders complained that Georgia still refused 
to hold talks with South Ossetia on its political status. 
  They feared that Georgia would use the treaty with Russia 
against South Ossetia and Abkhazia. 
  Russian Defense Minister Pavel Grachev, who arrived in 
Tbilisi today for preparations for Yeltsin's visit, stressed 
that the future of the military and political cooperation 
between Russia and Georgia partly depends upon the settlement of 
the political status of Abkhazia and South Ossetia. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

